To generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LATEX document, you need to use the following commands:

1.  `\tableofcontents` at the beginning of your document, before the `\begin{document}` command. This will generate the TOC.
2.  `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc. commands to create sections, subsections, and subsubsections.
3.  The `\setcounter{tocdepth}{<level>}` command to control the depth of the TOC.

Here's an example of how to generate a TOC automatically in a LATEX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\setcounter{tocdepth}{3}  % Set the depth of the table of contents to 3 (sections, subsections, subsubsections)

\tableofcontents  % Generate the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
    This is the introduction section.

\section{Section 1}
    \subsection{Subsection 1.1}
        This is a subsection of Section 1.
    \subsection{Subsection 1.2}
        This is another subsection of Section 1.

\section{Section 2}
    \subsection{Subsection 2.1}
        This is a subsection of Section 2.
    \subsubsection{Subsubsection 2.1.1}
        This is a subsubsection of Subsection 2.1.

\end{document}
```

In this example, `\setcounter{tocdepth}{3}` is used to set the depth of the table of contents to 3, meaning that sections, subsections, and subsubsections will be included in the TOC. If you want to include sections, subsections, and subsubsection in the TOC, you can set the counter to 4.

When you compile this document using `pdflatex`, the TOC will be generated automatically and will include the sections, subsections, and subsubsections.

